  "target_response": {
    "text": "Your data shows an association, but a thin one: across 8 tagged late-dinner days versus 34 comparison days in your recent log, next-day recovery averaged about 5 points lower. That's a link, not a cause — and with only 8 tagged days the pattern is graded low confidence, so treat it as a hypothesis rather than a finding. There's also a confound this data can't untangle: late dinners in your log tend to travel with later bedtimes, and either the meal timing or the shorter night could be carrying the effect, or both. The honest read is plausible but unproven. If you want a cleaner answer, keep tagging late dinners for another few weeks so the sample grows, and hold your bedtime steady on a few of those nights so the two factors stop moving together.",
